{"art": [{"brightcove": "", "caption": "David Dewhurst delivers a pre-convention howdy.", "id": 465, "infogram": "", "ndn": "", "ndnid": "", "other": "", "photo": null, "resource_type": {"id": 2, "name": "YouTube", "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/mediatype/2/"}, "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/media/465/", "title": "Dewhurst pre-convention video", "wibbitz": "", "youtube": "<iframe src=\"//www.youtube.com/embed/JdH9jfz5f_0?rel=0&wmode=opaque\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe>", "youtubeID": "JdH9jfz5f_0"}], "author": [{"email_address": "wgstexas@gmail.com", "first_name": "W. Gardner", "id": 122, "last_name": "Selby", "name_slug": "w-gardner-selby", "on_staff_page": 84, "phone": "", "photo": null, "publication": {"id": 3, "publication_name": "Austin American-Statesman", "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/publication/3/"}, "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/staffer/122/", "title": "Former PolitiFact Texas editor", "twitter": ""}], "canonical_url": "/texas/statements/2010/jun/17/david-dewhurst/dewhurst-says-believe-it-or-not-republican-state-c/", "edition": {"adkey": "Editions", "advalue": "Texas", "edition": "Texas", "edition_slug": "texas", "has_afterthefact": false, "id": 2, "index_page": false, "meter_name": "The Texas Truth-O-Meter", "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/edition/2/"}, "editor": [], "facebook_headline": null, "id": 1908, "in_future": false, "is_pundit": false, "make_public": true, "preview": true, "researcher": [{"email_address": "wgstexas@gmail.com", "first_name": "W. Gardner", "id": 122, "last_name": "Selby", "name_slug": "w-gardner-selby", "on_staff_page": 84, "phone": "", "photo": null, "publication": {"id": 3, "publication_name": "Austin American-Statesman", "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/publication/3/"}, "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/staffer/122/", "title": "Former PolitiFact Texas editor", "twitter": ""}], "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/statement/1908/", "ruling": {"adkey": "Truth-O-Meter", "advalue": "Mostly True", "id": 2, "resource_uri": "/api/v/2/statementruling/2/", "ruling": "Mostly True", "ruling_graphic": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/static.politifact.com/rulings/tom-mostlytrue.png", "ruling_slug": "mostly-true"}, "ruling_comments": "<p><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Warming up for last  week&rsquo;s Republican State Convention in Dallas, Lt. Gov. David Dewhurst  made a Texas-sized boast in a video posted on his campaign Web site  Wednesday. &ldquo;It may be hard to believe, &ldquo; Dewhurst said, &ldquo;but our  (Republican) state convention is actually larger than the Republican  National Convention.&rdquo;</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"><em>Getouttahere</em>!</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Dewhurst&rsquo;s campaign  spokesman, Mike Walz, said in an e-mail that Dewhurst&rsquo;s calculation was  based on comparing the number of delegates and alternates to this June&rsquo;s  state confab and the number of delegates and alternates chosen to  attend the 2008 Republican National Convention in Minnesota.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">First, Walz pointed to  About.com and CNN Web posts, both stating there were 2,380 delegates to  the party&rsquo;s national convention. Next, he noted a recent Dallas Morning  News article stating 12,000 GOP activists went to the state convention  and a Fort Worth Star-Telegram article stating more than 10,000  delegates and alternates were expected.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">We also asked the  Republican Party of Texas about its count of 2010 convention attendees.  Spokesman Bryan Preston replied that &ldquo;we have just under 12,000  delegates &amp; alternates. Add the guests and VIPs and we&rsquo;ll hit&rdquo;  15,000 to 16,000 participants.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Why so many people? For decades, state party  rules have provided one delegate for every 300 votes cast for the  Republican nominee in the latest governor&rsquo;s race, which explains why the  biennial gatherings are held in Dallas, Fort Worth, Houston and San  Antonio; other cities don&rsquo;t have halls big enough to cram such crowds  into one space.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Driven  by the ratio, the party&rsquo;s potential turnout of delegates and alternates  surged from nearly 10,000 in 1984 to more than 17,000 in 2004,  according to research by Clint Moore of Houston, a longtime member of  the party&rsquo;s Rules Committee. The number of permitted delegates and  alternates dipped to 11,500 in 2008 because Gov. Rick Perry saw a drop  in his vote haul in 2006 while fending off three major challengers.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Does that mean the  total delegate count could keep rising election after election, mostly  because of population growth?</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Nope. Delegates voted at last week&rsquo;s  convention to cap delegates at 9,000 starting with the 2012 state  convention. The decision ensures that Fort Worth, intended site of the  next two conventions, can comfortably serve as host city. The local  convention center has a fixed-seat capacity of about 10,500, according  to Eric Opiela, a former party executive director just elected to the  executive committee.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Nevertheless, the Texas delegate count this  year far surpasses the 2008 national convention&rsquo;s count.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">We wondered if there&rsquo;s  another way to compare the sizes of the state and national gatherings.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Bill Riggs, a  spokesman for the Republican National Committee, guided us to a study of  the economic impact of the 2008 convention on the host cities,  Minneapolis-St. Paul. The study, by the Minneapolis-St. Paul 2008 Host  Committee, states that 45,000 &ldquo;guests&rdquo; came to the Twin Cities for the  four-day gathering, driving more than $150 million in spending.  Separately, the Dallas Convention &amp; Visitors Bureau told us the  recent state convention delivered a local economic impact of more than  $6.3 million.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Riggs  also noted a news article published in May by the St. Petersburg  (Florida) Times stating that 50,000 delegates, protesters and reporters  are expected to attend the 2012 Republican National Convention in Tampa.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">So how does Dewhurst&rsquo;s  statement shake out?</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">This month&rsquo;s GOP state convention drew more  delegates than the 2008 national convention, but economic and other  indicators suggest the national convention ultimately draws more people.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Similarly, though  Dewhurst&rsquo;s boast is justified by one measurement, by another it doesn&rsquo;t  add up. We rate his statement Mostly True.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span></p>", "ruling_comments_date": "2010-06-16T17:52:00.912408", "ruling_date": "2010-06-17T06:00:00", "ruling_headline": "Dewhurst says believe it or not, Republican State Convention bigger than quadrennial national convention", "ruling_headline_slug": "dewhurst-says-believe-it-or-not-republican-state-c", "ruling_link_text": "He's counting delegates", "ruling_state": null, "source_documents": null, "sources": "<p><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">CNN, Election Center  2008, </span><a href=\"http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/primaries/results/scorecard/#val=R\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">&ldquo;Delegate  Scorecard,&rdquo; </span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">&nbsp;accessed June 14, 2010</span><br /> <span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span><br /> <span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Dallas Morning News,  news article, </span><a href=\"http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/news/politics/state/stories/061110dntexlocalgop.19e3626.html\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">&ldquo;Dallas  Republicans hope state convention delivers shot of energy,&rdquo; </span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">June 11, 2010</span><br /> <span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span><br /> <a href=\"http://alt.coxnewsweb.com/statesman/politifact/06152010_responsetopftexas.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">E-mail</span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">, response to  PolitiFact Texas, Sharron Pete, marketing/research specialist, Dallas  Convention &amp; Visitors Bureau, June 15, 2010</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://alt.coxnewsweb.com/statesman/politifact/06112010_bryanprestonemail.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">E-mail</span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">, response to  PolitiFact Texas, Bryan Preston, communications director, Republican  Party of Texas, June 11, 2010</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://alt.coxnewsweb.com/statesman/politifact/06112010_mikewalzemail.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">E-mail</span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">, MIke Walz, communications director, David  Dewhurst campaign, June 11, 2010</span></p>\r\n<p><span id=\"internal-source-marker_0.6288856041331711\" style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Fort Worth Star-Telegram,  news article, </span><a href=\"http://www.star-telegram.com/2010/06/05/2242225/tea-party-members-get-seat-at.html%20\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\">&ldquo;Tea Party  members get seat at the table for Texas GOP convention,&rdquo;</span></a><a href=\"http://www.star-telegram.com/2010/06/05/2242225/tea-party-members-get-seat-at.html\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\"> </span></a><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">June 5, 2010 (accessed  June 14, 2010)</span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000099; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; vertical-align: baseline; text-decoration: underline;\"> </span><br /><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline;\">Interview, Clint Moore, Houston, June 14, 2010</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"f